Example code to illustrate the API for cNMF on simulated data¶

  • Current as of August 30 2018
  • Email dkotliar@broadinstitute.org with questions

Environment setup to run cNMF and this example:¶

  • conda create -n cnmf_env python=3.6
  • source activate cnmf_env
  • conda install --yes --channel bioconda --channel conda-forge --channel defaults cython==0.28.2 fastcluster==1.1.24 jupyter==1.0.0 jupyterlab==0.32.1 matplotlib==2.2.2 numpy==1.12.1 palettable==3.1.1 pandas==0.23.0 scipy==1.1.0 && conda clean --yes --all
  • pip install git+https://github.com/scikit-learn/scikit-learn.git@3b24a4855db8564ddccb011228c9f4a51a519c9a
  • pip install --upgrade --no-cache-dir --upgrade-strategy=only-if-needed bhtsne==0.1.9 - only necessary if you want to generate the tsne output yourself

In [8]:
### The plot was just saved to ./example_data/example_cNMF/example_cNMF.k_selection.pdf
### We also output it here in the notebook
def plot_comparison(stability, errors, ax1=None):
    '''
    'Make a plot to determine the choice of K. Plots stability in blue
    and error in red against K on the X axis of the same plot with different
    scales depicted on the left / right side Y-axis.
    '''
    if ax1 is None:
        (fig, ax1) = plt.subplots()
    ax2 = ax1.twinx()


    ax1.plot(stability.index, stability.values, color='b')
    ax1.set_ylabel('Stability', color='b', fontsize=15)
    for tl in ax1.get_yticklabels():
        tl.set_color('b')
    #ax1.set_xlabel('K', fontsize=15)

    ax2.plot(errors.index, errors.values, color='r')
    ax2.set_ylabel('Error', color='r', fontsize=15)
    for tl in ax2.get_yticklabels():
        tl.set_color('r')

    ax1.set_xlabel('Number of Components', fontsize=15)
    return(ax1, ax2)



Kselection_stats = load_df_from_npz('./example_data/example_cNMF/example_cNMF.k_selection_stats.df.npz')
Kselection_stats.index = Kselection_stats['k']
(fig,ax) = plt.subplots(1,1, figsize=(3.5,3.5), dpi=500)
(ax1, ax2) = plot_comparison(Kselection_stats['stability'], Kselection_stats['prediction_error'], ax1=ax)
ax1.set_ylabel('Stability', color='b', fontsize=15)
ax2.set_ylabel('Error', color='r', fontsize=15)
ax.set_xlabel('K', fontsize=15)
ylim = ax1.get_ylim()
ax1.vlines(x=10, ymin=ylim[0], ymax=ylim[1], linestyle='--')
_ = ax1.set_ylim(ylim)

Based on the above plot, we would select K=10 as it is the K with the lowest error that has a very stable solution¶

Obtain the consensus matrix factorization estimates¶

In [9]:
## This is the command you would run from the command line to obtain the consensus estimate with no filtering
## and to plot a diagnostic plot. Instead of doing so, we will run it in the notebook so that a nice embedded figure
## gets made
consensus_cmd = 'python ./cnmf.py consensus --output-dir %s --name %s --local-density-threshold %.2f' % (output_directory, run_name, 2.00)
print(consensus_cmd)
#!{consensus_cmd}

python ./cnmf.py consensus --output-dir ./example_data --name example_cNMF --local-density-threshold 2.00
In [10]:
## Run consensus clustering before filtering using the API. Save a diagnostic clustergram PDF image
cnmf_obj = cNMF(output_dir=output_directory, name=run_name)
cnmf_obj._initialize_dirs()
cnmf_obj.consensus(k=10, density_threshold_str='2.00', show_clustering = True, close_clustergram_fig=False)

based on this, we might filter all spectra with mean distance > .01¶

import palettable
from matplotlib import rcParams
from collections import Counter

rcParams['font.family'] = 'sans-serif'
rcParams['font.sans-serif'] = ['Myriad Pro']

rcParams['axes.titlesize'] = 9
rcParams['axes.labelsize'] = 9
rcParams['xtick.labelsize'] = 7
rcParams['ytick.labelsize'] = 7

rcParams['xtick.major.pad']='1'
rcParams['ytick.major.pad']='1'

import matplotlib as mpl
label_size = 8

core_colors = type('CoreColors', (), {})

cnames = ['red', 'blue', 'green', 'purple', 'orange', 'yellow', 'brown', 'pink', 'grey']

def to_array_col(color):
    return np.array(color)/255.

for cname,c in zip(cnames, palettable.colorbrewer.qualitative.Set1_9.colors):
    setattr(core_colors, cname, np.array(c)/255.)
    
for cname, c in zip(['blue', 'green', 'red', 'orange', 'purple'],
                    palettable.colorbrewer.qualitative.Paired_10.colors[::2]):
    setattr(core_colors, 'pale_'+cname, np.array(c)/255.)
    
core_colors.teal = to_array_col(palettable.colorbrewer.qualitative.Set2_3.colors[0])
core_colors.brown_red = to_array_col(palettable.colorbrewer.qualitative.Dark2_3.colors[1])

# core_colors.light_grey = to_array_col(palettable.colorbrewer.qualitative.Set2_8.colors[-1])
core_colors.light_grey = to_array_col(palettable.tableau.TableauLight_10.colors[7])

core_colors.royal_green = to_array_col(palettable.wesanderson.Royal1_4.colors[0])

In [20]:
tsnedat = pd.merge(left=tsne_results, right=celldata, left_index=True, right_index=True)

tsnedat['extra-status'] = 'Normal'
tsnedat.loc[tsnedat['has_program'] & ~tsnedat['is_doublet'], 'extra-status'] = 'program'
tsnedat.loc[~tsnedat['has_program'] & tsnedat['is_doublet'], 'extra-status'] = 'doublet'
tsnedat.loc[ tsnedat['has_program'] & tsnedat['is_doublet'], 'extra-status'] = 'program & doublet'
In [21]:
color_map = np.array([0,2,4,6,8, 12,16,18, 1,3,5,7, 9])

cell_tableau20_color_id = color_map[tsnedat['group'].astype(int).values - 1].astype(int)
cell_tableau20_color = np.array(palettable.tableau.Tableau_20.colors)[cell_tableau20_color_id]/255.

activity_color = np.zeros((tsnedat.shape[0], 4))
activity_color[:, 3] = tsnedat['has_program'].astype(float)
doublet_color = np.array(palettable.tableau.TableauMedium_10.colors[5])/255.
In [22]:
normal_filter = tsnedat['extra-status'] == 'Normal'
doublet_filter = tsnedat['extra-status'] == 'doublet'
activity_filter = tsnedat['extra-status'] == 'program'
activity_and_doublet_filter = tsnedat['extra-status'] == 'program & doublet'

import matplotlib.gridspec as gridspec

fig = plt.figure(figsize=(1.5, 2), dpi=600)
gs = gridspec.GridSpec(3, 1, fig, 0,0,1,1,
                       hspace=0, wspace=0,
                       height_ratios=[0.2, 1.5, 0.3],
                       width_ratios=[1])

ax = fig.add_subplot(gs[1, 0],
          xscale='linear', yscale='linear',
          frameon=False, xticks=[], yticks=[])

x = tsnedat['TSNE1']
y = tsnedat['TSNE2']


curr_filter = normal_filter


ax.scatter(x[curr_filter], y[curr_filter],
          facecolor=cell_tableau20_color[curr_filter.values],
           edgecolor='none',
           rasterized=True, s=2)

curr_filter = activity_filter
ax.scatter(x[curr_filter], y[curr_filter],
          facecolor=cell_tableau20_color[curr_filter.values],
          edgecolor=activity_color[curr_filter.values], linewidth=0.33,
           rasterized=False, s=2)


curr_filter = doublet_filter | activity_and_doublet_filter
ax.scatter(x[curr_filter], y[curr_filter],
          c=doublet_color,
          edgecolor='none', marker='x', linewidth=0.4,
          s=1)

curr_filter = activity_and_doublet_filter
ax.scatter(x[curr_filter], y[curr_filter],
          facecolor='none',
          edgecolor=activity_color[curr_filter.values], linewidth=0.33,
           rasterized=False, s=2)

cmap = palettable.cartocolors.sequential.Sunset_7.get_mpl_colormap()

axes = axes.ravel()
for i in range(1, 11):
    sc = axes[i-1].scatter(tsne_and_usages['TSNE1'], tsne_and_usages['TSNE2'], c=tsne_and_usages[i],
                      cmap=cmap, vmin=0, vmax=1.,

    axes[i-1].set_title(i)
    axes[i-1].set_xticks([])
    axes[i-1].set_yticks([])
    
    
    
plt.tight_layout()
fig.delaxes(axes[11])
fig.delaxes(axes[10])
